    <h1>Constructors in Object-Oriented Programming (OOP)</h1>
    <p>
        Imagine you are building toys from a mold. 🧸 The <strong>class</strong> is the mold (blueprint),
        and the <strong>constructor</strong> is like the special tool that helps you set up each toy when it's made.
        It gives the toy its name, color, or size right when it's created!
    </p>

    <h2>Example 1: Student Constructor</h2>

    <!-- Code container -->
    <div class="code-container">
        <div class="code-header">
            Student Example
            <div class="toggle-wrapper">
                <label class="toggle-label">C#</label>
                <label class="switch">
                    <input type="checkbox" id="studentToggle">
                    <span class="slider round"></span>
                </label>
                <label class="toggle-label">C</label>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="code-content">
<pre><code class="language-csharp student-code">
public class Student
{
    public string Name { get; set; }
    public int Age { get; set; }

    // Constructor
    public Student(string name, int age)
    {
        Name = name;
        Age = age;
    }

    public void Study()
    {
        Console.WriteLine($"{Name} is studying.");
    }
}

// Creating an object using the constructor
Student student1 = new Student("Alice", 20);
student1.Study();
</code></pre>

<pre><code class="language-c student-code" style="display:none;">
#include &lt;stdio.h&gt;
#include &lt;string.h&gt;

struct Student {
    char Name[50];
    int Age;
};

// "Constructor-like" function in C
struct Student createStudent(char name[], int age) {
    struct Student s;
    strcpy(s.Name, name);
    s.Age = age;
    return s;
}

void Study(struct Student s) {
    printf("%s is studying.\n", s.Name);
}

int main() {
    struct Student student1 = createStudent("Alice", 20);
    Study(student1);
    return 0;
}
</code></pre>
        </div>
    </div>

    <p>
        👉 Explanation:
        <ul>
            <li>In C#, <code>Student("Alice", 20)</code> is calling the constructor to set up the new student with a name and age.</li>
            <li>In C, we don’t have real constructors, so we use a helper function <code>createStudent</code> that does the same job.</li>
            <li>When Alice is created, she is ready to <code>Study()</code> immediately.</li>
        </ul>
    </p>

    <h2>Example 2: Car Constructor</h2>

    <!-- Code container -->
    <div class="code-container">
        <div class="code-header">
            Car Example
            <div class="toggle-wrapper">
                <label class="toggle-label">C#</label>
                <label class="switch">
                    <input type="checkbox" id="carToggle">
                    <span class="slider round"></span>
                </label>
                <label class="toggle-label">C</label>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="code-content">
<pre><code class="language-csharp car-code">
public class Car
{
    public string Brand { get; set; }
    public string Color { get; set; }

    // Constructor
    public Car(string brand, string color)
    {
        Brand = brand;
        Color = color;
    }

    public void Drive()
    {
        Console.WriteLine($"{Color} {Brand} is driving!");
    }
}

// Using the constructor
Car myCar = new Car("Toyota", "Red");
myCar.Drive();
</code></pre>

<pre><code class="language-c car-code" style="display:none;">
#include &lt;stdio.h&gt;
#include &lt;string.h&gt;

struct Car {
    char Brand[50];
    char Color[50];
};

// "Constructor-like" function
struct Car createCar(char brand[], char color[]) {
    struct Car c;
    strcpy(c.Brand, brand);
    strcpy(c.Color, color);
    return c;
}

void Drive(struct Car c) {
    printf("%s %s is driving!\n", c.Color, c.Brand);
}

int main() {
    struct Car myCar = createCar("Toyota", "Red");
    Drive(myCar);
    return 0;
}
</code></pre>
        </div>
    </div>

    <p>
        👉 Explanation:
        <ul>
            <li>The constructor <code>Car("Toyota", "Red")</code> makes sure our car already knows its brand and color when it’s born.</li>
            <li>In C, we mimic this using <code>createCar</code>.</li>
            <li>As soon as the car is created, it’s ready to <code>Drive()</code>.</li>
        </ul>
    </p>

    <h2>Key Points About Constructors</h2>
    <ul>
        <li>Constructors are called automatically when an object is created.</li>
        <li>You can have multiple constructors (constructor overloading) with different parameters.</li>
        <li>If no constructor is defined, C# provides a default parameterless constructor.</li>
        <li>Constructors help make sure your object starts life in a proper, ready-to-use state.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
        🔗 Remember: Constructors work together with <a href="@Url.Action("Classes", "OOP")">Classes</a>.
        Classes are the <strong>blueprints</strong>, and constructors are the <strong>setup tools</strong> that prepare each object built from that blueprint.
    </p>

